{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Dm6CisStr6UnzAEoHsQ7dk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The new pod has the correct probe settings. Now let me wait for it to become Ready. \n\nThe probe settings are:\n- liveness: initialDelaySeconds: 60, timeoutSeconds: 10, failureThreshold: 6\n- readiness: initialDelaySeconds: 20, timeoutSeconds: 10, failureThreshold: 6\n\nMongoDB should start and respond to ping within 60 seconds. Let me poll for readiness.\n\nBUT - there's another important consideration. Even if pod-0 becomes Ready, pod-1 and pod-2 still need to be created and become Ready. With OrderedReady policy:\n- Pod-0 must be Ready before pod-1 is created\n- Pod-1 must be Ready before pod-2 is created\n\nI also need to check if the replica set has been initialized. Once all 3 pods are running, they need to form a replica set with rs.initiate() if it hasn't been done already. Looking at the previous events, it seems the replica set was already initialized since the pods were running before (they were just failing probes and getting killed by liveness checks). I need to verify this by checking if mongod is still running.\n\nSince the mongod.conf already configures `replSet: mongodb-replica`, MongoDB will start as part of a replica set, but the replica set still needs to be initialized with rs.initiate() if this is a fresh cluster. However, given this is an existing setup that's been running, the replica set should already be initialized—the pods just need to start successfully. I'll wait for pod-0 to become Ready and then monitor whether the probes pass with the new settings, giving it about 2-3 minutes to stabilize.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":234,"cache_read_input_tokens":57872,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":234},"output_tokens":26,"service